This paper deals with the performance analysis of a cache-enabled device-to-device (D2D) network with full-duplex (FD) communication. The paper discusses the impact of caching and interference on network performance, which are key factors in network information theory (cs.IT) and network optimization (cs.NI). The paper also considers the operating modes of D2D nodes, which can be seen as a system-level design problem in control systems (cs.SY). Additionally, the paper discusses content delivery, which is a topic in multimedia (cs.MM) and security (cs.CR) research.
